generated_description:  August Macke's "On the Street" (c. 1900-1950) exemplifies Fauvism's bold use of color and form. Set in a bustling urban environment, the painting captures the vibrancy of early 20th-century street life. The flattened perspective and vivid hues reflect the era's fascination with modernity and the influence of Expressionism. Houses and buildings frame the scene, symbolizing the intersection of human activity and architectural space. This work celebrates the dynamism of city life through its expressive style.
