generated_description:  Max Pechstein's "Dialogue" (1920) embodies Expressionism's emotional intensity and distortion. Reflecting post-WWI disillusionment, it portrays two figures in stark, angular forms, suggesting communication breakdown. The muted palette and fragmented composition mirror societal fragmentation. Pechstein's focus on human interaction critiques modern alienation, aligning with Expressionism's rejection of traditional aesthetics. This work captures the era's psychological turbulence and evolving human relationships amidst rapid societal change.  

