generated_description:  Maurice Estève's "Trigourec" (1972) exemplifies Color Field painting, a post-war abstract movement emphasizing color and form. Estève's vibrant hues and geometric shapes reflect mid-20th-century optimism and abstraction's evolution. The work's bold composition challenges traditional perspectives, aligning with the era's artistic experimentation. Estève's style bridges European modernism and American abstraction, showcasing the global exchange of artistic ideas during this transformative period. The painting's abstract forms invite personal interpretation, embodying the era's focus on emotional expression and viewer engagement.
