generated_description:  Ernst Ludwig Kirchner's "Street Scene" (c. 1913) embodies Expressionism's emotional intensity and urban alienation. Set in Dresden, it captures the frenetic energy of modern city life. Distorted figures and vibrant, clashing colors reflect psychological tension and societal upheaval. The painting critiques bourgeois conformity, emphasizing individuality amidst urban chaos. Kirchner's work mirrors the era's anxiety and fragmentation, resonating with the broader cultural shifts of early 20th-century Europe.
