generated_description:  Correggio's "Madonna del Latte" (1524) exemplifies Mannerist elegance, blending Renaissance naturalism with expressive distortion. Set against a dark backdrop, the Virgin's tender embrace and the playful angel highlight sacred intimacy. This work reflects the Counter-Reformation's emphasis on emotional engagement with faith, using soft chiaroscuro and vibrant colors to evoke spiritual warmth. Correggio's innovative use of sfumato and dynamic composition influenced later Baroque artists, bridging the gap between High Renaissance ideals and emerging Mannerist sensibilities.
