generated_description:  Fernand Léger's "The Breakfast" (1921) embodies Cubism's fragmented perspective, reflecting early 20th-century industrialization and mechanization. The geometric figures and objects symbolize modernity's dehumanizing effects. Set during mealtimes, it critiques traditional domestic roles, merging human forms with machine-like qualities. This painting captures the era's tension between human intimacy and technological advancement, challenging conventional artistic norms and societal structures. Léger's bold use of color and form underscores the evolving cultural landscape of the time.
