generated_description:  Jacopo Pontormo's "Portrait of a Young Woman" (c. 1525) exemplifies Mannerist portraiture, characterized by its elongated forms and subtle emotional depth. Set against a dark backdrop, the subject's poised demeanor and intricate attire reflect the period's emphasis on individuality and status. The small dog symbolizes fidelity, while the delicate jewelry highlights the sitter's refinement. This work captures the transitional phase between High Renaissance clarity and Mannerist complexity, showcasing Pontormo's mastery in evoking psychological nuance.
