generated_description:  Paolo Uccello's "Adoration of the Magi" (c. 1435) exemplifies Early Renaissance focus on perspective and narrative depth. Set against a detailed landscape, the scene blends sacred and secular elements, reflecting humanist ideals. The Magi's journey symbolizes the convergence of diverse cultures toward Christian salvation. Uccello's meticulous attention to detail and spatial arrangement underscores the era's transition from medieval flatness to a more realistic representation, aligning with the period's burgeoning interest in scientific observation and classical revival.
