generated_description:  Jan Steen's "Supper at Emmaus" (1668) captures a pivotal moment from the New Testament, reflecting Baroque drama and emotion. Set in a rustic inn, the scene portrays Jesus revealing himself to disciples post-resurrection. Steen's use of light and shadow emphasizes the miraculous recognition, while the intimate setting and everyday details humanize the divine event, aligning with 17th-century Dutch interest in relatable religious narratives. The painting underscores faith's integration into daily life during the Counter-Reformation era.
