generated_description:  Claude Monet's "Shadows on the Sea at Pourville" (1882) exemplifies Impressionism's focus on light and color. Set against the backdrop of Pourville's cliffs, the painting captures the transient effects of sunlight on water. Monet's use of broken brushstrokes and vibrant hues conveys the dynamic interplay of light, reflecting his fascination with natural phenomena. This work underscores the era's shift towards capturing immediate sensory impressions, a hallmark of late 19th-century art.
