generated_description:  Howard Hodgkin's "Girl on a Sofa" (1968) blends pop art with abstract expressionism. The bold red backdrop and graphic stripes reflect mid-20th-century design trends, while the abstract figure suggests a modernist reinterpretation of portraiture. Hodgkin's use of vibrant colors and simplified forms captures the era's cultural dynamism and evolving artistic language. The piece exemplifies the post-war shift towards abstraction and the influence of commercial aesthetics on fine art. Contextual details are limited.
