generated_description:  This minimalist sculpture by Daniel Dezeuze, titled "Par une for-t obscure III," from 1997, exemplifies post-war abstraction. Its repetitive geometric forms and vibrant orange evoke industrial aesthetics and the era's exploration of space and structure. The piece challenges traditional art boundaries, reflecting mid-to-late 20th-century cultural shifts towards conceptual expression and material experimentation. Minimalism's focus on form and color is evident, inviting viewers to engage with the work's physicality and spatial dynamics.
