generated_description:  Titian's "Perseus and Andromeda" (1556) embodies Mannerist drama and sensuality. Set against a tumultuous sea, Perseus rescues Andromeda, chained and vulnerable. This mythological scene reflects Renaissance humanism, celebrating heroism and female beauty. Titian's rich colors and dynamic composition highlight the tension and emotion, typical of his late style. The painting underscores the era's fascination with classical narratives and the artist's mastery in conveying dramatic storytelling within the cultural milieu of 16th-century Venice.
