generated_description:  Lentulov's self-portrait (1912) embodies Cubism's fragmented perspective, reflecting early 20th-century modernist ideals. The geometric abstraction challenges traditional portraiture, symbolizing a break from past conventions. Created during a period of artistic revolution, it captures Lentulov's exploration of form and color, mirroring the dynamic shifts in Russian art post-Revolution. This work highlights the artist's role in bridging European avant-garde influences with Russian artistic expression.
